external_knowledge:
- "Expected fuel consumption" is calculated by multiplying the typical fuel consumption rate of the flight type by the flight duration;
- "Actual fuel consumption" is the total fuel consumed during the flight, as recorded in the database;
- "Fuel-thirsty flights" refers to flights where the actual fuel consumption is greater than the expected fuel consumption.

- "Flight types" refer to different categories of aircraft, such as commercial or military;
- "Average fuel consumption" is the mean amount of fuel used per flight for each type;
- "Top 5" indicates the flight types with the highest average fuel consumption.

- Each flight can be metaphorically seen as a journey through the sky;
- The `flight_id` serves as a unique identifier, akin to a ship's name in a maritime logbook;
- `fuel_consumption` represents the fuel used during the flight, similar to the resources consumed on a long voyage.

- "Thirstiest birds in the sky" refers to flights with the highest fuel consumption;
- "Guzzled" refers to the amount of fuel consumed;
- "Average for their type" refers to the average fuel consumption of flights within the same flight type.

- "Aircraft type" refers to the model of the aircraft, such as Boeing 737 or Airbus A320;
- "Pilot name" is the full name of the pilot who flew the flight;
- "Fuel consumption" is the total amount of fuel used during the flight, measured in gallons or liters;
- "Average fuel consumption" is the mean fuel consumption for a given type of aircraft, calculated across all flights of that type.

- Flight types with IDs 1 and 2 represent commercial and military flights respectively;
- The performance metric is a numerical value that indicates how well the aircraft performed during the flight;
- 2023 is the year of interest for the flights.
